/ Welcome to nwawe a purely functional extensible programming language

(name = input<Name: >) / as you can see it is very LISP inspired, this prompts a input with a Name:  string before the actual input very Python-esque but what's with the <>?? you will see
(print<Hello!, *name>) / will print Hello! YourName as you can see <> are actually how you interact with functions and *var is used when using a variable as everything in <> atleast in input and print is automagically asumed to be a string
(print<"Hello! " + *name >) / this is the same but i've forced the Hello!  with a space to be a string!
/ Why not just use LISP you ask??
function{<a>,<b> :
    [sum]
    (a = input<a: >)
    (b = input<b: >)
    (sum = a * (b ^ 2) - b _ (a + 2) ) / a times b squared minus b divided by a + 2 _ can be also substitute by / or // (whole number dividing)
    [\sum] / his returns the sum variable
}

(print<function'<1>,<2>'>) / this is a simplified easier to read version
(print<function<1><2>>) / this is the same but harder to read you can see how quickly you can get confused
(print<function
    <1> /, a comma after this is not needed but can be used if you like it that way
    <2>
>) / here is a deconstructed version this also works

(print<function'
    <1>, /but when using the '' way of specifying arguments the comma is needed
    <2>
'>)

